description: From sticky +‎ beak; presumably from the metaphor of sticking one′s beak (“nose”) where it is not wanted (compare nosy).

entries.meaning: (Australia, New Zealand, colloquial) An overly inquisitive person, a nosey parker.
examples: I walked back towards the grinning stickybeak who took a few steps backwards before fleeing for the steamy safety of his laundry.

entries.meaning: (Australia, New Zealand, colloquial) An act of looking at or watching something, especially something which does not directly concern the one looking.
examples: It′s worth popping into the bar for a stickybeak.

verbs.description: stickybeak (third-person singular simple present stickybeaks, present participle stickybeaking, simple past and past participle stickybeaked)

entries.meaning: (Australia, New Zealand) To pry or snoop.
examples: Two of the more arrogant birds actually inspected the inside of the tent, clucking away to each other as they stickybeaked.
